   <mods:abstract>Is home overnight following the birth of his son; will return to Albany
            tomorrow. Since his last letter the convention has been occupied with the judiciary. A
            proposition to abolish the court of chancery and vest equity jurisdiction in the supreme
            court was debated and rejected as was Mr. Munro's plan. The vice-president's resolution,
            the object of which was to turn out the present Chancellor and judges, and the report of
            a committee headed by Mr. Munro, were also defeated. The judiciary will probably remain
            nearly as it is except that all judges of the county courts will hold office for five
            years. The radical party shows strength and is forming into a distinct section of the
            democratic party.</mods:abstract>
